===Noun===
{{en-noun|abilit|ies|-}}

# {{uncountable}} The quality or state of being able.<!--; power to perform, whether physical, moral, intellectual, [[conventional]], or legal; capacity; skill or [[competence]] in doing; [[sufficiency]] of strength, skill, [[resources]], etc.; -- in the ''plural'', faculty, [[talent]].-->
#: ''This wood has the '''ability''' to fight off insects, fungus, and mold for a considerable time.''
# {{countable}} A [[skill]] or [[competence]].
#* {{rfdate}} ''[[King James Bible'', "Acts" 11:29
#*: Then the disciples, every man according to his '''ability''', determined to send relief unto the brethren.
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:Francis Bacon|Francis Bacon]]
#*:Natural '''abilities''' are like natural plants, that need pruning by study - 
#* {{rfdate}} [[w:Thomas Babington Macaulay|Thomas Babington Macaulay]]
#*: The public men of England, with much of a peculiar kind of '''ability'''
# {{uncountable|countable}} A high level of skill or competence.
#: ''They are persons of '''ability''', who will go far in life.''
#: ''She has an uncanny '''ability''' to defuse conflict.''
# {{uncountable}} Suitability or receptiveness to be acted upon.
#: ''This phone has the '''ability''' to have its software upgraded wirelessly.''

